# Terraform & Script Operations

## Secret sources

All secrets live in two places — never in tracked files:

| Secret | Env var | Source |
|--------|---------|--------|
| DB password | `TF_VAR_db_password` / `DB_PASSWORD` | `.env.terraform` (sourced manually) |
| Bastion SSH CIDR | `TF_VAR_bastion_ssh_cidr` | `.env.terraform` (auto-detects current IP via `curl -s4 ifconfig.me`) |
| Bastion IP | `BASTION_IP` | Terraform output or project-context rule (`52.27.223.210`, may change on instance restart) |
| RDS hostname | `RDS_HOST` | Terraform output or project-context rule |

The file `terraform/environments/dev.tfvars` contains **redacted placeholders** for `bastion_ssh_cidr` and `db_password`. These placeholders are intentional — **never replace them with real values**.

## Running Terraform

```bash
# 1. Source secrets (sets TF_VAR_db_password and TF_VAR_bastion_ssh_cidr)
source .env.terraform

# 2. Use -var flags to override the redacted tfvars values
terraform -chdir=terraform plan \
  -var-file=environments/dev.tfvars \
  -var "bastion_ssh_cidr=$TF_VAR_bastion_ssh_cidr" \
  -var "db_password=$TF_VAR_db_password"

terraform -chdir=terraform apply \
  -var-file=environments/dev.tfvars \
  -var "bastion_ssh_cidr=$TF_VAR_bastion_ssh_cidr" \
  -var "db_password=$TF_VAR_db_password"
```

The `-var` flags take highest precedence in Terraform, so they cleanly override the placeholders in dev.tfvars without touching the file.

## Running database scripts

All scripts in `scripts/` that connect to RDS use an SSH tunnel through the bastion. They read connection details from environment variables:

```bash
BASTION_IP=52.27.223.210 \
RDS_HOST=football-backend-dev-db.cwrqrc8xrxdy.us-west-2.rds.amazonaws.com \
DB_PASSWORD=<password from .env.terraform> \
npx tsx scripts/<script>.ts [args]
```

### Common script commands

```bash
# Check current database state (table counts, migrations)
BASTION_IP=52.27.223.210 RDS_HOST=football-backend-dev-db.cwrqrc8xrxdy.us-west-2.rds.amazonaws.com DB_PASSWORD="$TF_VAR_db_password" npx tsx scripts/check-db.ts

# Run migrations
BASTION_IP=52.27.223.210 RDS_HOST=football-backend-dev-db.cwrqrc8xrxdy.us-west-2.rds.amazonaws.com DB_PASSWORD="$TF_VAR_db_password" npx tsx scripts/migrate.ts

# Load a season (e.g. full 2024)
BASTION_IP=52.27.223.210 RDS_HOST=football-backend-dev-db.cwrqrc8xrxdy.us-west-2.rds.amazonaws.com DB_PASSWORD="$TF_VAR_db_password" npx tsx scripts/load-season.ts --season 2024 --full-season

# Clear a season (dry run first)
BASTION_IP=52.27.223.210 RDS_HOST=football-backend-dev-db.cwrqrc8xrxdy.us-west-2.rds.amazonaws.com DB_PASSWORD="$TF_VAR_db_password" npx tsx scripts/clear-season.ts --season 2024 --dry-run
```

Tip: source `.env.terraform` first, then reference `$TF_VAR_db_password` in the DB_PASSWORD position to avoid pasting the raw password on the command line.

## Updating bastion access when IP changes

If SSH to the bastion times out, your public IP likely changed. Fix it without editing dev.tfvars:

```bash
source .env.terraform
terraform -chdir=terraform apply \
  -var-file=environments/dev.tfvars \
  -var "bastion_ssh_cidr=$TF_VAR_bastion_ssh_cidr" \
  -var "db_password=$TF_VAR_db_password" \
  -target=aws_security_group.bastion \
  -auto-approve
```

## SSH key

The bastion key is at `~/.ssh/football-bastion.pem`. Scripts reference it automatically.
